Note:
HTML Lexer

Tokenizes HTML documents into a stream of tokens for parsing.

Supports:
- HTML tags (opening, closing, self-closing)
- Attributes with values (quoted and unquoted)
- Text content
- Comments <!-- ... -->
- DOCTYPE declarations
- HTML entities (&nbsp;, &lt;, &gt;, etc.)
- CDATA sections

Token Types:
- TOKEN_TAG_OPEN - Opening tag start: <
- TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE - Closing tag start: </
- TOKEN_TAG_END - Tag end: >
- TOKEN_SELF_CLOSE - Self-closing tag end: />
- TOKEN_IDENTIFIER - Tag names, attribute names
- TOKEN_EQUALS - Attribute assignment: =
- TOKEN_STRING - Attribute values (quoted)
- TOKEN_TEXT - Text content between tags
- TOKEN_COMMENT - HTML comments
- TOKEN_DOCTYPE - DOCTYPE declaration
- TOKEN_ENTITY - HTML entity reference
- TOKEN_EOF - End of file
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_TAG_OPEN as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_TAG_END as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_SELF_CLOSE as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_TEXT as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_DOCTYPE as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_ENTITY as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 99

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A flat byte-array cursor plus line/column tracking is sufficient because HTML is parsed by character, not by Unicode codepoint, in this translator. Tracking line and column lets emitted tokens carry source positions for downstream diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven 8-byte slots: source bytes pointer, source byte length, current byte
position, current line (1-based), current column (1-based), in_tag flag
(1 while the cursor is between a tag's '<name' and its closing '>' / '/>',
0 in element content), and raw_tag (0 = none, 1 = inside a <script> body,
2 = inside a <style> body). The in_tag flag lets next_token distinguish
attribute identifiers from element text content; raw_tag lets it treat
script/style bodies as a single opaque text run rather than parsing the
markup inside them. Total record size is 56 bytes.
@End Implementation

Type called "Lexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    in_tag as Integer
    raw_tag as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single 48-byte token shape supports every TOKEN_* variant; punctuation tokens leave text/length as 0 while text-bearing tokens (identifier, string, text, comment, doctype, entity) point back into the source buffer rather than copying. Inlining position lets parsers attach diagnostics without re-querying the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six 8-byte slots: token_type (TOKEN_* constant), text pointer into source, byte length, line, column, metadata reserved for future flags.
@End Implementation

Type called "Token":
    token_type as Integer
    text as Integer
    length as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Initialising the lexer separately from tokenisation lets callers reuse a single source pointer across multiple parse passes (e.g., for incremental reparsing). Line and column start at 1 to match human-facing tooling conventions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Rejects null source. Computes source_length via string_length (treating source as NUL-terminated bytes). Allocates 56 bytes and initialises slot 0=source, 8=length, 16=0 (position), 24=1 (line), 32=1 (column), 40=0 (in_tag), 48=0 (raw_tag).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new HTML lexer

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer_size be 56
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Examination
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returning 0 at end-of-source lets every callsite use the same end-of-stream sentinel as a literal NUL byte. This avoids needing a separate "is at end" check before every peek.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position from offset 16 and source_length from offset 8; if position >= length returns 0; otherwise reads the byte at source+position.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Several constructs need multi-byte lookahead (e.g., "<!--" needs four characters of certainty before committing to comment mode, "</" needs two for closing-tag detection). A parametric peek avoids hand-rolling each lookahead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes peek_pos = position + offset; returns 0 if peek_pos exceeds source_length; otherwise reads the byte at source+peek_pos. Does not modify lexer state.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead by offset characters

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, peek_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Advancing must update position AND maintain the line/column counters so error messages can point at the right place. Newline (10) resets column to 1 and bumps line; all other bytes (including CR=13 alone) just bump column, matching the behaviour expected by Unix-style sources.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current position and source_length; refuses to advance past end. Reads the byte at position, increments position, then updates line/column: newline -> line+=1, column=1; other -> column+=1. Returns the consumed byte so callers can branch on it.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If char is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
HTML treats space, tab, LF, and CR as whitespace inside tags. Inline classification with explicit byte values keeps the lexer free of dependencies on a general character-classification library and is faster than table lookup for this 4-element set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if char is 32 (space), 9 (tab), 10 (LF), or 13 (CR), otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
HTML tag and attribute names start with an ASCII letter. Checking both A-Z (65-90) and a-z (97-122) ranges directly avoids any locale dependence.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if 65 <= char <= 90 or 97 <= char <= 122, otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit detection is needed because HTML attribute names and tag names allow digits after the first character. A single range check covers 0-9.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if 48 <= char <= 57, otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
HTML identifier continuation accepts letters, digits, hyphens ("data-id"), and underscores ("data_id" in some flavours). Bundling these into one predicate keeps the scan_tag_name loop simple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Composes is_alpha and is_digit, plus explicit 45 (hyphen) and 95 (underscore). Returns 1 on any match.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single allocator for every token variant guarantees consistent 48-byte layout regardless of which scan function produced it. Storing line/column at construction time captures the position before subsequent advances move the lexer past the token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes and writes token_type/text/length/line/column/metadata at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, text as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new token

    Let token_size be 48
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, text
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, metadata

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace Skipping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Whitespace between attributes inside a tag is non-significant and must be skipped so the next token starts at a meaningful byte. Outside tags whitespace is significant (it is text content), so this helper is intentionally scoped to in-tag use.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops calling peek_char and breaks on the first non-whitespace byte; otherwise advances. Uses is_whitespace for classification.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace_in_tag" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace inside tags only

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with char

        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Tag Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Tag and attribute names share the same lexical shape (identifier characters until a non-identifier byte). Scanning them with one routine keeps the lexer state-machine simple. Returning 0 on zero length protects callers from emitting empty identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position, line, and column before consuming. Loops advancing while is_alphanumeric holds. Computes length = end_position - start_position and constructs a TOKEN_IDENTIFIER whose text pointer is source+start_position (no copy).
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
When an opening tag's name is "script" or "style" the lexer must switch to
raw-text mode for the element body. Detecting this requires comparing the name
about to be scanned, case-insensitively, against the two raw-element names. This
helper peeks the upcoming name bytes without consuming them so the regular
scan_tag_name still produces the TOKEN_IDENTIFIER the parser expects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peeks bytes at the cursor against "script" then "style" using case-insensitive
folding and requires the byte immediately after the candidate name to be a
non-identifier byte (so "scripted" is not mistaken for "script"). Returns 1 for
script, 2 for style, 0 otherwise. Pure: does not advance the cursor.
@End Implementation

Process called "name_peek_equals" takes lexer as Integer, name as Integer, name_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Case-insensitively compare the upcoming tag name to a candidate

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than name_length:
        Let src_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, index
        Let expected be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with name, index

        Let folded be proc to_lower_ascii with src_char
        Let expected_folded be proc to_lower_ascii with expected

        If folded is not equal to expected_folded:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Let after_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, name_length
    Let after_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric with after_char
    If after_alnum is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "name_is_raw" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify the upcoming open-tag name as script (1), style (2), or none (0)

    Let is_script be proc name_peek_equals with lexer, "script", 6
    If is_script is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_style be proc name_peek_equals with lexer, "style", 5
    If is_style is equal to 1:
        Return 2
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "scan_tag_name" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan tag name or attribute name

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric with char

        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Attribute values may use either single or double quotes; capturing the opening quote and using it as the terminator handles both uniformly without two separate scanners.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records line/column, consumes the opening quote (and remembers its byte as quote_char), records the post-quote start_position, then loops advancing until peek_char matches quote_char or reaches end-of-source (0). Computes length, consumes the closing quote, and emits TOKEN_STRING with text pointing into the source buffer between the quotes.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_attribute_value" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan quoted attribute value

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let quote_char be proc advance_char with lexer

    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to quote_char:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Text Content Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Text content runs from the current position until either a tag-start ("<", byte 60) or an entity-start ("&", byte 38) is encountered. Stopping on entity makes it the parser's job to emit a separate entity token rather than burying the entity inside text bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position, line, column. Loops advancing while peek_char is not 0,
60, or 38, tracking whether any non-whitespace byte was seen. A run with no
content bytes is inter-element formatting whitespace, which is insignificant in
the document tree; rather than emit a whitespace-only text token (which would
not survive the emitter's re-indentation on round-trip) the scanner discards it
and returns the next real token. A zero-length run (cursor already on a stop
byte) also defers to next_token so the dispatcher makes forward progress.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_text" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan text content between tags

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let saw_content be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 60:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 38:
            Break
        End If

        Let char_ws be proc is_whitespace with char
        If char_ws is equal to 0:
            Set saw_content to 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    If length is equal to 0:
        Return proc next_token with lexer
    End If

    If saw_content is equal to 0:
        Return proc next_token with lexer
    End If

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TEXT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comment Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The comment delimiter "<!--" has already been confirmed by next_token's lookahead, so this routine consumes exactly four bytes to step past it, then scans the body until the terminator "-->" using multi-byte lookahead at every step.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances four bytes to skip "<!--". Captures start_position after the delimiter. Loops: at each iteration peeks for hyphen (45) and uses peek_ahead 1 and 2 to look for "->"; on match breaks before consuming. After the loop, computes length, then advances three bytes to consume "-->". Emits TOKEN_COMMENT pointing into the source between delimiters.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan HTML comment <!-- ... -->

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 45:
            Let next1 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2

            If next1 is equal to 45:
                If next2 is equal to 62:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMENT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DOCTYPE Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
DOCTYPE declarations end at the first ">" and do not allow ">" inside. The
TOKEN_DOCTYPE value carries only the internal subset (e.g. "html") rather than
the "<!DOCTYPE ... >" envelope, because the backend re-applies the envelope when
emitting. Storing only the subset makes the declaration round-trip exactly: the
emitted "<!DOCTYPE html>" re-lexes to the same "html" value instead of nesting a
second envelope.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
The cursor enters on "<" with "<!D"/"<!d" already confirmed by the dispatcher.
Advances past "<!", then past the alphabetic keyword ("DOCTYPE"/"doctype"), then
skips any whitespace. Records start_position at the internal subset and loops
advancing until ">" (62) or end-of-source (0), consuming the ">" when found.
Emits TOKEN_DOCTYPE whose text covers only the internal subset between the
keyword and ">".
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_doctype" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan DOCTYPE declaration

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Consume "<!" then the DOCTYPE keyword
    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let kw_char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let kw_alpha be proc is_alpha with kw_char
        If kw_alpha is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    proc skip_whitespace_in_tag with lexer

    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 62:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let close_char be proc peek_char with lexer
    If close_char is equal to 62:
        proc advance_char with lexer
    End If

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOCTYPE, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Entity Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entities terminate either at semicolon (well-formed) or at a whitespace (forgiving recovery for malformed input). Capturing the leading ampersand in the token text simplifies later entity-resolution because the resolver can dispatch on prefix style ("&#" vs "&name").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position at "&", advances past it, then loops: on EOF (0) break, on semicolon (59) advance and break, on space (32) break without consuming. Emits TOKEN_ENTITY with text pointing at source+start_position covering the full entity.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_entity" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan HTML entity &name; or &#123;

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 59:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 32:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ENTITY, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Raw-Text (script/style) Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The contents of <script> and <style> elements are CDATA/raw text in the HTML
spec: '<' inside them does not start a tag and '&' does not start an entity.
Parsing them as markup would corrupt any embedded JavaScript ("a < b") or CSS.
The lexer therefore captures the entire body verbatim as one TOKEN_TEXT,
stopping only at the matching end tag ("</script" or "</style", followed by
'>' or whitespace), which is detected with case-insensitive lookahead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position. Loops: on EOF (0) break; when the current byte is '<'
(60) and peek_ahead 1 is '/' (47), compares the following bytes against the
expected end-tag name (raw_tag 1 -> "script", 2 -> "style") case-insensitively;
on a full match it breaks with the cursor parked on the '<' so the normal
dispatcher emits the closing tag. Otherwise advances one byte. Emits a single
TOKEN_TEXT covering [start_position, end_position). Clears raw_tag to 0 so the
dispatcher resumes ordinary content tokenisation after the end tag.
@End Implementation

Process called "to_lower_ascii" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Fold an ASCII uppercase letter to lowercase; pass others through

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return char plus 32
        End If
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Process called "raw_matches_at" takes lexer as Integer, name as Integer, name_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Case-insensitively check that the end-tag name follows "</" at the cursor

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than name_length:
        Let offset be index plus 2
        Let src_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, offset
        Let expected be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with name, index

        Let folded be proc to_lower_ascii with src_char
        Let expected_folded be proc to_lower_ascii with expected

        If folded is not equal to expected_folded:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: The matched name must be followed by '>' or whitespace, not more name bytes
    Let after_offset be name_length plus 2
    Let after_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, after_offset

    If after_char is equal to 62:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let after_ws be proc is_whitespace with after_char
    If after_ws is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "scan_raw_text" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan a <script>/<style> raw-text body verbatim

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let raw_tag be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    Let name be "script"
    Let name_length be 6
    If raw_tag is equal to 2:
        Set name to "style"
        Set name_length to 5
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 60:
            Let slash be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            If slash is equal to 47:
                Let is_end be proc raw_matches_at with lexer, name, name_length
                If is_end is equal to 1:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0

    If length is equal to 0:
        Return proc next_token with lexer
    End If

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TEXT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
This dispatcher distinguishes the seven major HTML lexical categories using one to four bytes of lookahead. The "<" branch needs the deepest lookahead because "<!--" (comment) and "<!D" (DOCTYPE) share the "<!" prefix; otherwise the dispatch is a flat character-class switch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1) End-of-source -> TOKEN_EOF. 2) "<" with "!--" lookahead -> scan_comment; with "!D" or "!d" -> scan_doctype; with "/" -> emit TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE; otherwise TOKEN_TAG_OPEN. 3) ">" -> TOKEN_TAG_END. 4) "/" with ">" lookahead -> TOKEN_SELF_CLOSE. 5) "=" -> TOKEN_EQUALS. 6) Quote (34 or 39) -> scan_attribute_value. 7) "&" -> scan_entity. 8) Whitespace inside tag context -> skip and recurse. 9) Alpha -> scan_tag_name. 10) Otherwise -> scan_text.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from HTML source

    Let in_tag be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let raw_tag be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    Note: In element content with a pending script/style body, capture it raw
    If in_tag is equal to 0:
        If raw_tag is not equal to 0:
            Return proc scan_raw_text with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 0:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: A '<' may begin a comment, DOCTYPE, closing tag, or opening tag in any
    Note: context; it always interrupts content text.
    If char is equal to 60:
        Let next1 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2
        Let next3 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 3

        If next1 is equal to 33:
            If next2 is equal to 45:
                If next3 is equal to 45:
                    Return proc scan_comment with lexer
                End If
            End If

            If next2 is equal to 68:
                Return proc scan_doctype with lexer
            End If

            If next2 is equal to 100:
                Return proc scan_doctype with lexer
            End If
        End If

        If next1 is equal to 47:
            Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
            Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 3
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
        End If

        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_OPEN, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: Inside a tag (open name, attributes, or close tag) tokens are markup
    If in_tag is not equal to 0:
        If char is equal to 62:
            Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
            Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_END, 0, 0, line, column, 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 47:
            Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

            If next is equal to 62:
                Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
                Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SELF_CLOSE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
            End If
        End If

        If char is equal to 61:
            Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
            Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUALS, 0, 0, line, column, 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:
            Return proc scan_attribute_value with lexer
        End If

        If char is equal to 39:
            Return proc scan_attribute_value with lexer
        End If

        Let is_ws_tag be proc is_whitespace with char
        If is_ws_tag is equal to 1:
            proc skip_whitespace_in_tag with lexer
            Return proc next_token with lexer
        End If

        Let is_alpha_tag be proc is_alpha with char
        If is_alpha_tag is equal to 1:
            Note: The first identifier in an open tag is the tag name; detect
            Note: script/style so the body can be captured as raw text, then
            Note: move to the attribute sub-state.
            If in_tag is equal to 1:
                Let raw_kind be proc name_is_raw with lexer
                If raw_kind is not equal to 0:
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, raw_kind
                End If
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 2
            End If
            Return proc scan_tag_name with lexer
        End If

        Note: Any other byte inside a tag (malformed) advances one to guarantee
        Note: forward progress and is reported as a single-byte text token.
        Return proc scan_text with lexer
    End If

    Note: Element content: entities and text only
    If char is equal to 38:
        Return proc scan_entity with lexer
    End If

    Return proc scan_text with lexer
End Process

Note: End of HTML Lexer
